<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How much does it cost to raise a child to 18?", answer: "The USDA's most-cited estimate from its 2015 Expenditures on Children by Families report puts the total at about $233,610 for a middle-income family — and that figure has only grown with inflation. Adjusted to 2026 dollars, the comparable number is roughly $310,000 for a middle-income family in a mid-cost area. Lower-income families spend around $215,000 and higher-income families around $455,000. These figures cover housing, food, transportation, healthcare, childcare/education, clothing, and miscellaneous expenses, but exclude college." },
  { question: "What is the biggest expense in raising a child?", answer: "Housing is consistently the largest line item at about 29% of the total — bigger homes, additional bedrooms, and family-friendly neighborhoods all cost more. Childcare and education come second at 16%, especially during the first 5 years of life when daycare averages $10,000–$25,000 per year per child in many US metros. Transportation (15%), food (18%), and healthcare (9%) round out the top categories. Clothing (6%) and miscellaneous (7%) are minor by comparison." },
  { question: "Do additional children cost less?", answer: "Yes — the USDA estimates a 'multi-child discount' of about 24% per additional child due to shared housing, hand-me-downs, bulk buying, and economies of scale. A family with two children doesn't spend twice as much as a family with one; it spends roughly 1.76x. A family with three children spends about 2.5x. The biggest savings come from sharing bedrooms and reusing baby gear, clothes, toys, and books across siblings." },
  { question: "How much does college add?", answer: "College is on top of the $233K–$310K. The College Board's 2024 report puts the average cost of a 4-year public in-state college at about $108,000, and a 4-year private at about $235,000 — including tuition, room, board, and books. State universities for in-state students are the cheapest path; private and out-of-state schools double or triple the cost. 529 plans, scholarships, and financial aid can dramatically reduce out-of-pocket spending." },
  { question: "Is it really that expensive to have a kid?", answer: "The USDA totals look terrifying but they're spread over 18 years — $310,000 / 18 / 12 = about $1,435 per month per child, on average. That's less than the average mortgage payment. Most parents adjust by living in slightly bigger homes, driving slightly older cars, eating out a little less, and accepting a slower retirement savings rate. The real challenge isn't any single year — it's the long-term compounding of small daily decisions." }
]) %>

